<br>
I've tried enchanter/cleric, and it's HARD, and I've been dual-comping for nearly a year and a half.  The problem is that when you're busiest with the enchanter is also when you're busiest with the cleric.  It's really hard to split attention between mesing 4 mobs and making sure no one is dying while they're getting mes'd.<br>
<br>
Tricks are as mentioned above.<br>
<br>
1. Hotkeys!  My druid has 3 as /target sinsa.  6 is heal on druid and mes on chanter.  5 is DD on both.  Try to get the hotkeys of similar nature in the same spot on both accounts.<br>
<br>
2. Put the character that has to do the most clicking on the right (assuming you drive mouse with your right hand).  The healer can be on the left 'cause you can use F1-F6 to select the members of your group for healing.<br>
<br>
3. Avoid using the mouse on the left side -- in tight situations, you can easily find yourself using the wrong mouse.<br>
<br>
4. ALWAYS put the characters on the same comps.  If you swap around, you'll try to mes with the cleric and heal with the chanter.  That doesn't usually work.<br>
<br>
5. Make sure your group knows you are dual-comping.  Most people understand that means you can miss tells or might not be paying enough attention to healing.<br>
<br>
6. Decide which is your primary focus.  Make sure that the druid in the group knows that in tight situations, they need to be ready to heal, as the cleric is likely to respond slowly on heals while you're mesing something.<br>
<br>
7. Have sound on both machines.  You can use the sound to tell you if your spells fizzled or if you're getting hit and don't realize it.  Warning: chanters in illusion make different noises when getting hit, and you might not realize you're dying if you let the noise be your only clue.<br>
<br>
=== A word about primary focus ===<br>
<br>
This is a little story about a time hunting Eboots.  We had 2 good groups, but short on clerics.  So I was dual-comping chanter and cleric.  Skyal was there -- 6 levels higher than me, I think -- as his ench.  But I was so focused on playing chanter that I wasn't focused on the cleric enough, and the puller died a few times.<br>
<br>
Moral: let the other chanter be primary chanter, and focus on the role of cleric.<br>
<br>
=== Other comments ===<br>
<br>
I can dual-comp kite.  Wolfy and Sin &quot;solo'd&quot; most of the way to 50 by kiting.  It got tricky on multiple pulls, but I got good enough eventually to be able to quad-kite.<br>
<br>
People who catch me in Seb lately have seen me with 3 characters, working hard on 60.  Wolfy and Sinerip (druid and rogue) would normally stay out of the group, so we effectively had 8 people gaining xp for 6.  This can be WILD experience.  Most of the time, I'm heavily complemented on how well I do that.<br>
<br>
Okay, that's the back-patting.  I'm no slouch at dual-comping.<br>
<br>
I won't dual-comp primary chanter and primary healer in a &quot;real&quot; situation.  I can pull to Seb zone-in that way, but I wouldn't go to disco like that.<br>
<br>
It's strictly a matter of attention.  Playing chanter during a 4-pull requires a lot of attention.  That's the same time the cleric also has the heaviest workload.  Someone is going to die.<br>
<br>
If you have controlled pulls, or if you trust that the tank can take a heck of a beating, maybe you can pull it off.  But it's probably the hardest combination available.<br>
<br>
